  }
];
---

<Layout title={`${reviewData.title} Review: ${reviewData.testingTime} of Testing`} description={reviewData.description}>
  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is Namecheap website builder good for beginners?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, Namecheap is beginner-friendly with a simple drag-and-drop interface. However, modern AI builders like Durable, Mixo, or Wix offer significantly better AI features, more templates, and professional designs. Namecheap is fine if you already buy domains from them, but not compelling otherwise."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I export my Namecheap website?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No, Namecheap doesn't offer code export. Your website is tied to their hosting platform. If you leave, you'll need to rebuild from scratch. For code export options, consider Framer ($15-35/mo), 10Web ($4-60/mo), or Webflow ($23-59/mo)."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does Namecheap compare to GoDaddy?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Both are domain registrars with website builders. GoDaddy has slightly better templates and AI features, while Namecheap is often cheaper for domains. Both are adequate if you're already a customer, but neither competes with dedicated website builders like Wix or Framer in terms of features and design quality."
        }
      }
    ]}
  />

  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">
    <div class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-orange-600 font-semibold mb-4">REVIEW</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">{reviewData.title} Review</h1>
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 mb-6">{reviewData.description}</p>
      <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">
        <span>Updated: {reviewData.date}</span>
        <span>-</span>
        <span>{reviewData.testingTime} of hands-on testing</span>
      </div>
      <TestingBadge score={reviewData.score} />
    </div>

    <!-- TESTING EVIDENCE -->
    <TestingEvidence tool={reviewData.title} evidences={testingEvidences} />

    <!-- UNEXPECTED FINDINGS -->
    <div class="mb-12">
      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-50 to-amber-50 border-[3px] border-orange-300 p-6 md:p-8">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-2">Unexpected Findings After 16 Hours</h2>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wider font-black">What nobody tells you about Namecheap</p>

        <div class="space-y-4">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-orange-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">Client with 20 domains: "convenience" became prison</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Had 20 domains, used builder for "everything connected." Can't add blog, change header, make portfolio full-width. Stuck because migrating 20 domains is hassle. Domain convenience = builder lock-in.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-orange-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">"Modern photography portfolio" prompt â†’ 2016 template with handshakes</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Asked for modern portfolio. Got 2016 template with stock handshakes. Durable: modern content in 30s. Framer: gorgeous designs. Namecheap: template matching from decade ago.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-orange-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">Namecheap $2-9/mo vs Hostinger $3-8/mo - why pay same for less?</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Same price range. Hostinger: better templates, AI, performance. Namecheap: domain integration? 5 minutes setup once. Not worth settling for worse builder indefinitely.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-orange-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">Domain management = 5 min/year, website = hours daily</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">"Everything in one place" sells. Reality: domains take 5 min/year regardless. Spend hours in builder. Why prioritize domain convenience over builder quality? Convenience illusion.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="text-orange-600 font-black text-xl flex-shrink-0">!</span>
            <div>
              <p class="font-black text-gray-900">7.0/10 overall, 7/10 convenience, 5/10 quality/features</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-1">Great domain registrar. Website builder exists to capture customers who don't know better. Buy domains from Namecheap, build site elsewhere. That's the real answer.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Quick Verdict -->
    <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-50 to-yellow-50 border-[3px] border-orange-300 rounded-xl p-6 md:p-8 mb-12">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class="text-4xl">ðŸ”—</span>
        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900">Great for Domains, Mediocre for Websites</h2>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-orange-500/10 border-l-[4px] border-orange-500 p-4 mb-5">
        <p class="text-orange-800 font-bold text-lg">
          Score: 7.0/10 - Only if you're already trapped in their ecosystem
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700">
        <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong>Namecheap is great for buying domains.</strong> Their website builder? Not great. Basic AI features, dated templates, limited customization. This feels like a legacy product with AI bolted on.
        </p>

        <div class="bg-white/80 p-4 rounded-lg border border-orange-200">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 uppercase tracking-wider font-bold mb-2">The One Use Case</p>
          <p class="text-gray-800">
            <strong>If you already use Namecheap for domains:</strong> Sure, add the builder. It's convenient having everything in one place. But if you DON'T use Namecheap? There's zero reason to start now.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-orange-700">The problem:</strong> You're paying for convenience, not quality. For the same price, Hostinger has better templates and Framer has better AI. Namecheap's builder exists to upsell domain customers.
